9] Java Asynchronous Programming


   📌 Future:
   Future represents the result of an asynchronous computation.
   It provides a way to retrieve the result of the computation once it's available.
   The get() method is used to retrieve the result, which blocks until the computation is complete.
   Synchronous programming with Future typically involves blocking calls, where the main thread waits for the result of the computation.
   Asynchronous Programming with CompletableFuture:
   CompletableFuture:

   📌 CompletableFuture is an extension of Future that provides more flexibility and functionality for asynchronous programming.
   It allows you to chain multiple asynchronous operations together in a fluent and non-blocking manner.
   You can create CompletableFuture instances manually or use factory methods to compose them.
   It provides methods like thenApply(), thenAccept(), and thenCompose() for composing actions to be executed asynchronously.
   CompletableFuture supports error handling through methods like exceptionally() and handle().

   📌Spring Webflux:

     It is a reactive, non-blocking web framework for building modern, scalable web application in Java

9] CompltableFuture:

   A CompltableFuture is used for asynchronous programming. Asynchronous programming means writing non-blocking code.
   It runs a task on a separate thread than the main application thread and notifies the main thread about its progress,
   completion or failure.


   The difference has to do with the Executor that is responsible for running the code.
   Each operator on CompletableFuture generally has 3 versions.

   thenApply(fn) - runs fn on a thread defined by the CompleteableFuture on which it is called,
   so you generally cannot know where this will be executed. It might immediately execute if the result is already available.

   thenApplyAsync(fn) - runs fn on a environment-defined executor regardless of circumstances.
   For CompletableFuture this will generally be ForkJoinPool.commonPool().

   thenApplyAsync(fn,exec) - runs fn on exec.
   In the end the result is the same, but the scheduling behavior depends on the choice of method.


