10] Java ReentrantLock - fairness, tryLock and more:

    https://www.baeldung.com/java-concurrent-locks

    1] lock.getHoldCount();   // Get lock count:

        2] Fairness : After a  thread release the lock, now longest waiting Thread will get a lock

           - byDefault locks will be unfair
           - lock=new ReentrantLock(true) for fair

        3] Fair lock

           Advantages:     Equal chance for all threads
           DisAdvantages:  Slower

        4] UnFair lock

           Advantages:    Faster ( More Throughput)
           DisAdvantages:  Possible Thread Starvation

        5] tryLock()

           Check if lock is available, don't block

           - Doesn't honor fairness
           - Workaround is to use tryLock timeout with 0 seconds
           - boolean tryLock() – This is a nonblocking version of lock() method.
             It attempts to acquire the lock immediately, return true if locking succeeds.

        6] Timeout tryLock(time)

           - lockAcquired = lock.tryLock(5,Seconds);
           - boolean tryLock(long timeout, TimeUnit timeUnit) – This is similar to tryLock(),
             except it waits up the given timeout before giving up trying to acquire the Lock.
